{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_inxs_ver01/data/sn82014519/00414183566/1930102801/1054.xml":{"full_text":"NEW BRITAIN DAILY HERALD. TUESDAY, OCTOBER 28, 1930.\nMillionaire Manufacturers War\nFor Political Supremacy In Bay\nState Contest for Senate Seat\nMorrow's Participation\ni\nAlso Lends Vigor to New\nJersey Contest for Sena\ntorial Toga.\nlioslon, .Mass., Oct. 28 (UP) The\nUnited .States senutoriiil buttle:, with\nprospects of a c!oku light, seems to\nhave, captured most of the interest\nsurrounding the forthcoming elec\ntion in Massachusetts.\nThis race involves two millionaire\nmanufacturers, William M. Butler,\nformer United States senator, former\nchairman of the republican national\ncommittee and close friend of Cal\nvin Coolidge; 'and Marcus A. Coo\nlidge, long prominent in Massachu\nsetts state politics.\nButler is bone dry and a stalwart\nsupporter; of the Hoover prohibition\npolicy. Coolidge. is dripping wet.\nButler, although ho has filled an\nunexpired term as United States\nnator. never has been elected to\ntiiat office. He was defeated by Sen\nntor David I. Walsh in 1026. While\nCoolidge has long been identified\nivith state politics he never has mld\nan important public oftice.\nUnemployment Isl.ik\nAltlioush prohibition is one of the\noutstanding issues of the campaign,\nunemployment seems lo be the ma\njor one.\nIn this connection. Butler has\ncontended that thB nation is not ex\nperiencing hard times but merely a\nperiod of hesitancy. He has said\nthat while there may be a little de\npression now. there would be re-jl\nbard times if the democrats got into\noflice and started tinkering with the\ntariff. I\nButler believes Unit, every state\nshould a'dopt the 4S-hour law in in\ndustry which prevails in Massachu\nsetts. Ho lias described this law as\nwise and humane, and has express\nred the belief that federal action will\nbe necessary to lUnin nationwide\nenactment.\nThe Nye campaign fund investi\nrfating committee was to have come\nlo Massachusetts several weeks ago\nto consider charges by Conrad\n;'rooker. general counsel of the lib--Vral\ncivic league, .hat Butler had\n;becn paying substantial sums 0\nmoney to labor leaders in connec\ntion with his campaign. Senator,\nGerald P. Nye, however, deferred\nbearing of the muttT until after\nelection, though he has written to\nboth Butler and Coolidge for infor\nmation pertaining to campaign acti\nvities. In his campaign. Coolidge had\n'Charged Butler with insincerity m\nhis advocacy of the national 48\nhou,r law. Characterizing his own\nlbor record as unassailable. Cool\nidge has declared that Butler has\nopposed every humane labor meas\nure advocated in the state and has\nbeen a consistent opponent of th;\n48-hour law for women ant! chil\ndren. Record As.saileel\nAt the same time, Coolidge's la\nbaro record has been assailed in re\npublican quarters, it being charged\nthat as a matter of expediency, sev\neral years ago, he moved virtually\nhis entire lathe-manufacturing plant\nfrom Kitchburg. Mass., his honn\ncity, to Seneca Falls, N. Y., disre\ngarding the welfare of his Kitchburg\nemployes.\nCoolidge has sought lo belittle,\nthese allegations by stressing the\nfact that on October 15 the Fitch\nburg Central Labor Union adopted\na resolution to the effect that as an\nemployer Coolidge never was hostile\nor unfriendly to labor.\nGovernor Frank G. Allen, republi\ncan dry seeking re-election, is an\nother millionaire manufacture. He\nis regarded as a strong candidate,\nhaving defeated General Charles H.\nCole, wet democrat, two years ago\ndespite the fact that in the same\nelection Al Smith carried Massachu\nsetts. Joseph B. Ely, Westfield lawyer\nand dripping wet democrat, is Gov\nernor Allen's opponent. He is ex\npeeted to poll a heavy vote, espe\ncially in western Massachusetts,\nwhich section of the. state has no'\nfurnished a governor for many\n5 ears.\nPresCTited $1,000 Clteck\nDuring the recent primary in\nThieh Ely defeated, among other\ncandidates, former Mayor John F.\nFitzgerald of Boston, James M\nCurley, the present mayor of Boston\nand an outstanding democratic lead\ner, threw his support to Fitzgerald\ndespite the fact that Fitzgerald had\nretired because of illness. Curley' be\nlittled Ely's ability at that time, but\nafter Ely had been nominated\npromptly hopped on the Ely batvl\n\"wagon in the interest of party har\nmony, presenting Ely a $1,000 check\nAt the democratic slate convention.\nNot only do the senatorial an 3\ngubernatorial contests present\nclean-cut wet-dry battles, but ther;\nIs to be a referendum on the ques\ntion whether the baby Volstead act\n(state prohibition enforcement law!\nshould be repealed.\nIn the last election, a non-mandatory\nwet referendum was supported\nby a substantial majority.\nBoth wet and dry organizations\nor Massachusetts have been extra\nordinarily active in the present cam\npaign in connection with the forth\ncoming referendum which will def\ninitely decide the fate of th\" state\ndry law.\nJersey Campaign Healed\nNewark. N. J., Oct. 27 P) The\ncontest for United States senator in\nNew Jersey has robbed this year's\ncampaign of the usual apathy of an\noff-year.\nDvvight W. Morrow was drafted as\na candidate just a few months ago\nmid the nation took notice. He was\na fresh figure in the game of poli\nties which now has him pitted\n\"ciTainst Alexander Simpson and Miss\nThcima Parkinson, democrats and\nrgainst the nominees of the national\nprohibition, communist and socialist\nparties.\nSimpson in p. candidate for the\nT'i)l \"rtinnui i,rm of six year:-'.\n2d3 l'.i. Uinren lor ll'.-j unc:,pircJ\nteem of Walter E. Edge, and Mor\nrow for both terms. Miss Parkin\nson, blonde, bright-eyed young lady\nwent from Smith college into poli\ntics. For the most part. New Jersey\nhas turned its eyes and ears toward\ntwo men, heard, both of them re\nnounce prohibition, one of them laud\nPresident Hoover. The other bit\nterly assails him.\nUses New Method\nMorrow's method; of campaigning\nis almost unheard of. He answers\nno charges. He does not mention\nhis adversaries, neither does he\ncriticise the issues the raise. He\nmakes no specific requests for votes\ntor himself; he asks only that the\npeople exercise their franchise. He\npractices, as he preaches, temper\nance and tolerance in the discussion\nof controversial matters. Such were\nhi tactics in the primary campaign,\ntoo. and he was nominated by more\nthan 300,000 votes over his closest\ncompetitor in a four-cornered con\ntest. Simpson, spectacular of speech,\nmeticulous of manner, has raised a\nwarning against support of endorsers\nof President Hoover and the na\ntional administration, left business\ndepression continue. He jabs at\nMcrrovv. formerly a member of the\nfirm of J. P. Morgan company, de\nsignating him us the choice of the\nfinanciers, unable lo comprehend\nthe -point of view of the man in\nthe street, the man who works in\nhis undershirt when he can find\nwork in these troubled times.\nThe democratic candidate is a\nman of satire, of slogans. He has\nliuill his campaign on allega\ntions and alliterations. Morrow is\n\"Dvvight Worship Morrow\" to Simp\nson and the \"Oracle of Englewood.\"\nA vole for the republican, Simpson\nwarns, is signification of approval\nof \"Morrow, Morgan and Misery.\"\nMorrow is chided for his economic\ndissertations and his probing into\nthe causes of industrial depression\nand unemployment.\nMorrow, warmly commending\nPresident Hoover, holds that the\ncourage and fortitude of the people\nwill constitute the major contribu\ntion to the return of prosperity. He\npleads against exaggeration of busi\nness denression and unemployment.\nMentioned for Presidency\nSince his declaration for repeal of\nthe ISth amendment. Morrow has\nbeen advanced as a potential candi\ndate for the presidency. He refuses\nto take such talk seriously. The\nboom took root in the light of his\nbackground as a lawyer, banker, and\nsuccessful abibassador to troubled\nMexico; in the light of his work at\nthe London naval conference, on the\nallied maritime transport commis\nsion and the national aviation in\nquiry commission. Just a few days\nago, however, he announced he\nlooked forward wtlj \"confidence and\nwith pleasure\" to voting foi the re\nnomination and reelection of Presi\ndent Hoover in 1932.\nThe senatorial campaign has tak\nen for its own the lion's share of\nthe state's interest. The electorate is\naware of local issues, aware a full\ndelegation of 12 will be elected next\nmonth to the house of representa\ntives, a complement of GO sent to\nthe state assembly and eight state\nsenators chosen. It knows these\nfacts, but in most instances the\nchoices already have been made\nand interest lags.\nOf the 12 representatives in the\nhouse, only two are democrats. Four\nof the districts now represented by\nrepublicans are conceded to be in\ndoubt, namely the third, sixth,\neighth and ninth. Three former\nrepresentatives are. seeking come\nbacks. In the third district, in a field of\nfive candidates Thomas M. Gopsill,\nrepublican and William 11. Sutphin,\ndemocrat, are waging an intense\nstruggle for the seat relinquished by\nRepresentative Harold G. Hoffman\nwho became utato commissioner of\nmotor vehicles. Gopsill endorsed\nMorrow's prohibition stand and\nSutphin is an out and out wet.\nRepresentative Randolph Perkins\nof the sixth district has maintained\nhis attitude in favor of prohibition,\nwhile Archibald C. Hart, democratic\ncandidate and three-time member of\ncongress, is a wet.\nRepresentative Franklin W. Fort,\nunsuccessful candidate in the repub\nlican primary for nomination to the\nUnited States senate as upholder of\nthe, JSth amndment. will relinquish\nhis office next March and two con\nfirmed wets are making a strong\nfight to succeed him. Peter A. Ca\nviccbia won the republican nomina\ntion and Daniel F. Minahan, former\ndemocratic representative. is op\nposing him, in the ninth district..\nFred A. Hartley. Jr., who won\nelection as representative from the\neighth district by a slight majority\nover Paul J. Moore in a presidential\nyear is seeking reelection. In the re\nmaining districts, the incumbents\nwere virtually assured to be return\ned. In all districts, the socialists and\ncommunist parties entered candi\ndates. NevV Jersey this year also is voting\non a $100,000,000 bond issue refer\nendum. The money would be dis\ntributed to permit expenditure of\nSS3.000.oon for highway improve\nment and railroad grade crossing\nelimination: 510.000. 000 for institu\ntional rehabilitation and $7,nno.ni)0\nto purchase potable water supplies.\nbesieging the doors. President Hoov\ner has decided to continue a silent\npolicy towaid the congressional elec\ntion a week from today.\nThe president has declined ail\nalong to exert any direct influence\nupon the electorate, even though his\ncontrol of congress is at stake. He\nwill continue to keep hands off down\ntn the final mnnient. it is learned on\nhighest authority. j\nWi n-jrl wilt he trt t ii n ev.\nample to the voters by tilling out a\nballot for himself today or tomor\nrow to be mailed to California. It\nwill be sent by air mail to his home\nat Palo Alto along with the vote of\nMrs. HoovtT.\nElection night the president will\nremain in his study getting the re\nturns by a special United Press wire\nand by radio.\nHOOVER REFRAINS FROM\nACTIVITY IN CAMPAIGN\n'COUNT ARRESTED\nIN POLICE PROBE\nRobert Miller Picked Up on\nBroadway by Officers\nNew York. Oct. :S CP Robert\nMiller, alias \"The Count.\" who has\nbeen sought for questioning in con\nnection with the mysterious shooting\nof Jack \"Legs\" Diamond, was in the\nhands of police today.\nHe was picked up on Broadway\nlast night and escorted to an uptown\nhotel where he was held incommuni\ncado for examination by detectives\ntoday.\nPolice said he told them he had\ntalked with Diamond in the Hotel\nMonticello on Sunday morning two\nweeks ago when Diamond was shot,\nbut left before the shooting. He said\nwhen he heard of the attack he be\ncame paniestricken and fled to\nBedford, Mass. While there he told\npolice, he consulted with his attor\nney regarding a charge in Boston\non which he is at liberty under $15,\n000 bail.\nAttention was directed lo Miller\nat the time of the shooting when\npolice mound a cablegram address\ned to him in Diamond's room say\ning that arrangements could be made\nto get Diamond into Germany for\n$3,000.\nPolice Commissioner Mulrooney\nsaid Miller told him ho had been in\nDiamond's room discussing a ship\nment of whiskey which he and Dia\nmand planned to import. He said\nhe was planning to go to Germany\nint Diamond's place fo arrange for\nthe shipment.\nPresident Will Send His Vote to\nCalifornia By Air\nMall\nWashington, Oct. 2S (UP) Al\nthough the White House radio is\ntuning in the speeches of political\nleaders and campaign managers are\nFUNURAIi TOMORROW\nNew York. Oct. 28 (UP) The\nfuneral of Harry Payne Whitney,\nsportsman and financier, will be\nheld at 1 0 a. m. tomorrow at St.\nBartholomew's church. Services will\nhe private and burial will be at\nWoodlawn cemetery.\nGasoline excise tax collections\nfor August reached a total of $633,\n49S.61 in Mississippi.\nMAGS (38TH) ANNIVERSARY\nSALE OF\nMEN'S\nSHOES\nWe have placed on sale several hundred pair of Shoes made for\nNeftleton at greatly reduced prices.\nWe won't quote former prices, but you can take our word for it\nthat the savings are substantial.\nImported Spats are now being featured at $2.45\n(ONE WEEK ONLY)\nReductions Throughout the Store\n&SONS\nKUPPKNHEfMER CLOTHES KNOX HATS NETTLETON SHOES MANHATTAN\nSHIKTS LONG'S FURNISHINGS LUGGAGE BOYS' APPAltEL STORTING\nGOODS UNIFORMS GILLETTE DE LUXE RAZOR SETS GIFTS\nLEATHER NOVELTIES FOUNTAIN FEN SETS LADIES'\nHANDCRAFTED LEATHER TURSES.\nm\nmjini4mr4liiiiii;iWlWlWlW\nWEDNESDA\nID A ID\nat RAPHA\nY AS USUAL\nAlN DAY\nNew Britain's\nBIGGER and BETTER\nDept. Store\nJ nfjjl jimi j tnnrj j txsirj ltitnr nni 